    <div class="bsw-faq-list">
        <div class="bsw-faq-item">
            <input type="checkbox" id="bsw-faq-1" class="bsw-faq-toggle" />
            <label for="bsw-faq-1" class="bsw-faq-q">Does this require replacing our existing weld controllers?</label>
            <div class="bsw-faq-a">No, the monitoring system typically connects to the data output already produced by
                modern weld controllers, reading current, voltage, and force signals without requiring a controller
                replacement. For older analog controllers without digital output, a retrofit sensor kit can capture
                equivalent data during the pilot phase. A quick equipment audit during rollout determines exactly what
                each gun needs before any commitment is made, and specifics can be reviewed through <a
                    href="https://calendly.com/contact-heavyvehicleinspection/30min">book a demo</a>.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="bsw-faq-item">
            <input type="checkbox" id="bsw-faq-2" class="bsw-faq-toggle" />
            <label for="bsw-faq-2" class="bsw-faq-q">How does weld schedule auto-tuning stay within our approved process
                window?</label>
            <div class="bsw-faq-a">Auto-tuning operates strictly within the process parameters already approved in your
                weld schedule documentation, making only small adjustments within that validated window rather than
                introducing new, unvalidated settings. Any adjustment outside the approved range requires manual
                engineering sign-off, so process control ownership stays with your team at all times. This keeps the
                system compliant with existing PPAP and process validation requirements.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="bsw-faq-item">
            <input type="checkbox" id="bsw-faq-3" class="bsw-faq-toggle" />
            <label for="bsw-faq-3" class="bsw-faq-q">How far in advance can electrode wear actually be
                predicted?</label>
            <div class="bsw-faq-a">Depending on the weld application and material stack, electrode wear trends typically
                become detectable hundreds of weld cycles before the tip would produce an out-of-spec nugget, giving
                enough lead time to schedule tip dress or replacement during a planned changeover rather than as an
                unplanned stop. Prediction accuracy improves over the first several weeks of monitoring as the model
                learns the specific wear pattern for each gun and application.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="bsw-faq-item">
            <input type="checkbox" id="bsw-faq-4" class="bsw-faq-toggle" />
            <label for="bsw-faq-4" class="bsw-faq-q">Can this reduce our destructive weld testing sample size?</label>
            <div class="bsw-faq-a">Many body shops use continuous electrical signature monitoring as supporting evidence
                alongside their existing destructive test program, and some are able to work with their quality system
                to adjust sampling frequency once monitoring has demonstrated consistent correlation with test results.
                This is a plant-specific decision that typically involves your quality engineering team, and questions
                on how other customers have approached it can be directed to <a
                    href="https://heavyvehicleinspection.com/support">support</a>.</div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="bsw-faq-item">
        <input type="checkbox" id="bsw-faq-5" class="bsw-faq-toggle" />
